suggestions:
I don't want to name names (it's not GIUSEPPE! because it feels mean and I think it's not something done on purpose) BUT I think it might be a good idea to help the coaches get to know how to teach?

Codebar is fantastic and I've been coming since the early days. It's great that it has expanded so much but that also means that perhaps coaches  and students end up a bit less supported. I found that my experience of codebar really depends on the soft-skills of the coach. 

Teaching is not an easy thing, and having worked in the tech industry, I think that the 'soft skills' are very different from being a teacher. It's basically about making your student feel as comfortable as possible, reassuring them that there are 'no stupid questions' etc. I used to be a teacher, and it took a long time to get out the 'I feel awkward' phase to the 'ok, my job is to make students feel as comfortable as possible so that they are in a safe space to make mistakes and learn'. I think that is a totally different environment to the traditional office where you have to transmit information is the most efficient way possible.

I think that a short pdf/reminder document/coaches page could be really helpful. e.g:

Teaching skills

Please spend a few minutes getting to know your student
Ask them how they found codebar
What do they hope to do with their new coding skills in future
If they struggle with anything in particular with coding
What their day job is/if they are studying.
Reassure them that there are no silly questions!

Remember to spend equal amounts of time interacting with both students. (I know it can be tricky!) But it is your responsibility to check in with them how they are - they should not have to interrupt you.

If they ask a difficult question you can just smile and laugh, you don't have to be an expert on everything.

Remember that a student can be sensitive, please make sure your student feels welcome at all times. They need patience and reassurance!


It also might be worth holding a 'teaching skills' workshop. But obviously there'd be lots of work involved in that! Anyway, just an idea. 

Keep up the good work codebar!!!!!!!
